Package xxl.core.collections.queues.io

Class xxl.core.collections.queues.io.BlockBasedQueue extends StreamQueue implements Serializable

Serialized Fields

container

Container container
The container is internally used for storing the blocks that contains the serialized elements of the queue.

blockSize

int blockSize
The size of a block stored in the container. Every block stored in the container contains blockSize bytes of serialized data.

bytes

int bytes
The number of bytes stored by blocks in the container.

readBlockId

Object readBlockId
The id of readBlock, i.e. the block the queue currently reads from.

readBlockOffset

int readBlockOffset
The offset of readBlock, i.e. the block the queue currently reads from.

writeBlockId

Object writeBlockId
The id of writeBlock, i.e. the block the queue currently writes to.

writeBlockOffset

int writeBlockOffset
The offset of writeBlock, i.e. the block the queue currently writes to.

readBlock

Block readBlock
The block the queue currently reads from.

writeBlock

Block writeBlock
The block the queue currently writes to.

dummyBlock

Block dummyBlock
A dummy block that is used for getting a new id when a new write block is created. When creating a new write block, the dummy block is inserted into the container in order to get a valid id for the write block. When the creation of the write block is finished, the the dummy block is updated by the write block.

outputStream

OutputStream outputStream
The output stream is used for writing serialized elements to the queue. It is set to an output stream, that writes given bytes to the current write block. When the current write block is full, a new block is inserted into the container. In order to be able to determine the next block, when reading the serialized data, the id of the new block is stored at the end of the old write block. The output stream implicitly adjusts the number of bytes contained by the queue.

dim

int dim

a

dist

Distance<T> dist
The distance function used for the object space.

d

double[] d
Stores the distances between the pivot-objects. d[k] is the distance between a[k] and b[k]. Used for effectiveness.

data

TeeCursor<E> data
Given objects of the object space. A tee cursor* is used because in order to compute the pivot elements in advance one must scan the data 2*k times, i.e. the complexity of locating the pivot elements is O(2kn) whereas n denotes the number of objects in the cursor.

See Also:
Cursor, TeeCursor

Indicates wether the tee cursor has been used at least one time.

Serialized Fields

cdfMode

boolean cdfMode
If a cumulative distribution function is interpolated respectively approximated, the resulting interpolate needs to be one for all values right "beside" the interval. This flag indicates that the spline is in cdf mode, i.e., evaluating the spline interpolate at x with x > maximum causes the spline to return 1.0 instead of 0.0.

grid

double[] grid
grid constituting the approximation interval

fvalues

double[] fvalues
grid values of the function to interpolate

a

double[] a
This array contains values, which are necessary for determining the Bezier-coefficients of the spline. They constitute the lower subdiagonal of the matrix A, which has to be solved to determine the polynomials coefficients.

b

double[] b
This array contains values, which are necessary for determining the Bezier-coefficients of the spline. They constitute the upper subdiagonal of the matrix A, which has to be solved to determine the polynomials coefficients.

rightSide

double[] rightSide
This array contains the divided differences of the function values. It constitutes the right side of the LGS, whose solution is necessary for determining the Bezier-coefficients.

mu

double[] mu
The solution of the LGS A * mu = rightSide. With those values the Bezier-coefficients are determined.

bezier

The Bezier-coefficients are necessary for invoking the spline.

This array contains the distances between the nodes of the grid.

This array contains, if known, the two values of the first derivative of f at the borders.

Serialized Fields

bits

long[] bits
The bits in this BitSet. The ith bit is stored in bits[i/64] at bit position i % 64 (where bit position 0 refers to the most significant bit and 63 refers to the least significant bit).

precision

int precision
The user-relevant number of bits stored by this BitSet. This number can be choosen smaller than the size of a bit set, showing that the user does not need the whole precision. This possible loss of precision results in a better performance when comparing bit sets.
